# Popovers must always stack above their trigger surface

Every floating UI element — popover, dropdown menu, combobox list, tooltip, toast, or nested confirmation modal — must render **above** whatever surface opened it. This is non-negotiable. Don't ship a popover that can disappear behind a dialog.

## Why this rule exists

The recipe detail view (and any future modal like it) is a native `<dialog>` opened via `showModal()`. The browser renders `showModal`-ed dialogs in a special **top layer** that sits above everything else in the document and that `z-index` cannot beat. Anything portaled into `<body>` with a default `createPortal`, Radix `Portal`, or Base UI `Portal` will render **underneath** the dialog — the menu opens, the user just can't see it.

We solved this with a shared `top-layer host` tracker. Any popover that portals must use it.

## The rule

If you are adding **anything that portals** (i.e. renders into a different DOM root than its trigger), its portal target **must** be the active top-layer host when one is set. Use the helper:

```tsx
import { useTopLayerPortalContainer } from "@/lib/top-layer-host";

const container = useTopLayerPortalContainer();

// React portal:
createPortal(<Popover />, container);

// Radix portal:
<DropdownMenu.Portal container={useTopLayerHost() ?? undefined}>…</DropdownMenu.Portal>

// Base UI portal:
<Menu.Portal container={useTopLayerHost() ?? undefined}>…</Menu.Portal>
```

`useTopLayerPortalContainer()` returns:

- the currently-open native `<dialog>` element, when one is open via `showModal()`
- `document.body`, otherwise (or `null` during SSR — the helper already guards this, so gate rendering on it with `container && createPortal(…, container)`).

This works for **every** kind of floating surface:

- Searchable selects / comboboxes (`SearchableSelect`)
- Dropdown menus (Base UI `@base-ui/react` — our current primitive library)
- Any future Popover, Tooltip, HoverCard, ContextMenu, Select (Base UI, Radix, or otherwise)
- Custom "modal card" confirmations that you portal into the DOM
- Toast containers (see `AppToaster`)

## What to do

1. **Never** call `createPortal(…, document.body)` directly for a floating UI surface. Route through `useTopLayerPortalContainer()` instead.
2. **Never** leave a Base UI or Radix `Portal` without a `container` prop for anything that can be rendered inside a modal surface. Pass `container={useTopLayerHost() ?? undefined}`.
3. **Don't** try to fight the native dialog with `z-index`. It cannot be beaten. Always portal into the dialog instead.
4. If you add a new modal-like container that participates in the top layer (another `<dialog>` + `showModal`, a `popover` attribute element, etc.), call `setTopLayerHost(el)` when it mounts and clear it on unmount, matching `RecipeDetailDialog`'s pattern. That way everything in the system stacks correctly above it automatically.
5. If you add a new portal-based primitive, write a short comment pointing to this rule and to `lib/top-layer-host.ts`.

## Where this is enforced today

- `app/recipes-next/src/lib/top-layer-host.ts` — the store, the hook (`useTopLayerHost`), and the container helper (`useTopLayerPortalContainer`).
- `app/recipes-next/src/components/recipe-detail-dialog.tsx` — the producer that registers the native `<dialog>` as the top-layer host.
- `app/recipes-next/src/components/searchable-select.tsx` — example portal consumer using the hook.
- `app/recipes-next/src/components/recipe-detail-overlay-chrome.tsx` — example Base UI Menu consumer using the hook.
- `app/recipes-next/src/components/recipe-instructions-editor.tsx` — example Base UI Menu consumer for the per-step actions menu.
- `app/recipes-next/src/components/app-toaster.tsx` — example toaster consumer.
- `app/recipes-next/src/components/recipe-detail-editor.tsx` / `recipe-ingredients-editor.tsx` / `ingredient-delete-button.tsx` — nested confirmation modals consuming the hook.
